The "if" statement in Java is a fundamental control flow statement that allows you to execute a block of code if a specified condition is true. It is used to make decisions based on conditions or expressions.

The basic syntax of an "if" statement in Java is as follows:

```java
if (condition) {
    // code to be executed if the condition is true
}
```

Here's a more detailed example:

```java
int x = 5;
if (x > 10) {
    System.out.println("x is greater than 10");
} else {
    System.out.println("x is less than or equal to 10");
}
```

In this example, the condition `x > 10` is evaluated. If it is true, the code inside the "if" block is executed, and if it is false, the code inside the "else" block is executed.

You can also use "if-else if-else" statements to check multiple conditions:

```java
int x = 5;
if (x > 10) {
    System.out.println("x is greater than 10");
} else if (x == 5) {
    System.out.println("x is equal to 5");
} else {
    System.out.println("x is less than 5");
}
```

Additionally, you can use the "if" statement with logical operators to combine conditions:

```java
int x = 5;
int y = 10;
if (x > 5 && y < 10) {
    System.out.println("x is greater than 5 and y is less than 10");
}
```

It's worth noting that you can also use the "if" statement with the ternary operator to concisely express simple conditional statements:

```java
int x = 5;
String result = (x > 10)? "x is greater than 10" : "x is less than or equal to 10";
System.out.println(result);
```

Remember to always use meaningful variable names and comments to make your code readable and maintainable.

